// TEST: exec_py_unicode_print
// EXPECT: output "check=âś“ arrow=â†’ yen=ÂĄ"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Prints multibyte (non-ASCII) characters. On POSIX every target encodes stdout
// as UTF-8, so this passes regardless. Its real purpose is to lock in the
// Python entry-point UTF-8 stdout guard (Q-py-windows-utf8): on Windows, Python
// defaults stdout to the locale codepage, so a unicode `print` raises
// `UnicodeEncodeError` / mojibakes. The entry module (`main.py`) now emits
// `sys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding="utf-8")`, making Windows output match the
// POSIX targets. The fixture's assertion only DIFFERS on Windows, but it is a
// durable regression marker that unicode output round-trips byte-for-byte.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn main() -> Void {
  println("check=âś“ arrow=â†’ yen=ÂĄ")
}
